```python
def is_prime(n):
    if n <= 1:
        return False
    elif n <= 3:
        return True
    elif n % 2 == 0 or n % 3 == 0:
        return False
    i = 5
    while i * i <= n:
        if n % i == 0 or n % (i + 2) == 0:
            return False
        i += 6
    return True
```

This function works by first checking if the number is less than or equal to 1 (in which case it is not prime), or if it is less than or equal to 3 (in which case it is prime). It then checks if the number is divisible by 2 or 3. If it is, then it is not prime.

If the number passes these initial checks, the function then checks if it is divisible by any number up to its square root (since a larger factor of the number would be a multiple of a smaller factor that has already been checked). It does this by starting at 5 and checking every 6th number (i.e., 5, 11, 17, 23, etc.), as well as the number 2 greater than each of these (i.e., 7, 13, 19, 25, etc.). This is because all primes are of the form 6k ± 1, for some integer k.

If the function makes it through all of these checks without finding a factor, then the number is prime.
